PARLIAMENT President Jacob Zuma on Thursday threw his weight behind the controversial revised Mining Charter published by Mineral Resources Minister Mosebenzi Zwane. Yes, I believe firstly, the minister gave the briefing and consultation, including (to)the cabinet and what the minister is doing has been approved by the Cabinet, Zuma said in the National Assembly during his quarterly question-and-answer session.READ: Moody's slams Mining Charter The President brushed aside criticism of the charter by the Chamber of Mines of SA, unions, and his own ruling African National Congress, who are concerned about the impact the charter could have on jobs in the sector.The addition of "naturalized citizens" as BEE in the #MiningCharter is done by Guptas through their stooge. Zwane. It Must be rejected.The revised targets in the mining sector include that mining houses should have 30 percent black ownership to be shared among employees, communities and black entrepreneurs.Mining rights holders who have complied with the previous target of 26 percent have to top up to 30 percent within 12 months. Those applying for prospecting rights would be required to have a minimum of 50 percent plus one black person shareholding .READ: Markets fall after new mining charter is published In the wake of the charter being gazetted, the Chamber of Mines threatened to take the minister to court to interdict him from implementing the targets.African News Agency